  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Suspicious Activity Reporting\n- Monitoring transactions\n- Filing reports on unusual financial activity\n- Reporting potential money laundering to authorities\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees on detection\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\n4. Risk assessment\n- Evaluating customer and transaction risks\n- Implementing enhanced due diligence for high-risk clients\n\n5. Record keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Preserving documentation for specified periods\n\n6. Regulatory compliance\n- Following laws like the Bank Secrecy Act\n- Cooperating with government investigations\n- Submitting required reports to financial authorities\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, substantial fines, and potential criminal charges for financial institutions.\n\nThese requirements aim to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the global financial system.",
